{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492954"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:51:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:51:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.45,0.13,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1191"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3465"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9124"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of left iliac fossa pain, constipation and a general feeling of malaise and anorexia. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. There is mild and localised tenderness in the left iliac fossa. She would rather not be admitted to hospital unless necessary. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E White cell count: 9.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0) \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 5 mg/L (\u0026lt;5). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes and renal function: normal. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal CT scan: scattered sigmoid diverticulae with thickening of the wall of the sigmoid and pericolic fat stranding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Outpatient review","Oral antibiotics and outpatient review","Admit, intravenous antibiotics, complete gut rest and repeat CT in 24 hours","Admit, intravenous antibiotics, complete gut rest and colonoscopy in 24 hours","Admit, intravenous antibiotics and laparoscopic washout"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with typical clinical characteristics of diverticulitis such as left iliac fossa pain. However, her inflammatory markers are within normal limits. On CT imaging, diverticula outpouchings and colonic wall thickening can be seen, with pericolic fat stranding. Importantly, pericolic or distant abscesses were not seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiverticulitis management is based on its severity, which is classified based on the Hinchey classification. The Hinchey classification is separated into:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 0 - mild clinical diverticulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 1a - confined pericolic inflammation or phlegmon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 1b - pericolic or mesocolic abscess\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 2 - pelvic, distant intra abdominal or retroperitoneal abscess\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 3 - generalised purulent peritonitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 4 - generalised faecal peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplicated diverticulitis is when an abscess, fistula or perforation occurs, and therefore Hinchey stage 1b-4 is complicated while Hinchey stage 0 and 1a is uncomplicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen treating uncomplicated diverticulitis, inpatient admission is not required. \u003Cstrong\u003EOutpatient review\u003C/strong\u003E is all that is required to manage uncomplicated diverticulitis, along with conservative measures of analgesia, hydration and restricted oral intake. It\u0027s important to note that recent evidence has led to a significant change in care: oral antibiotics are no longer routinely recommended for uncomplicated diverticulitis in well, immunocompetent patients. This represents a shift from traditional practice and has been incorporated into multiple country guidelines. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E might still be considered in certain situations such as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eimmune compromise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eright-sided diverticulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efailure to improve after 72 hours of conservative treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf a patient had complicated diverticulitis, either diagnosed clinically or on CT, then admission as an inpatient, complete gut rest, and IV antibiotics should be initiated. The patient can then either be admitted for emergency surgery (typically Hartmann\u0027s procedure) or urgent surgery (an anterior resection 6-8 weeks post diverticulitis episode). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat CT\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used if symptoms of the diverticulitis are not improving after antibiotic treatment as an inpatient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E should not be conducted if a patient has an active flare up of diverticulitis as it is prone to perforating. A colonoscopy should only be conducted 6-8 weeks post diverticulitis episode, and only if the patient has not had a colonoscopy in the past two years. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic washout\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as a laparoscopic lavage) is a safe intervention that can be used to treat perforated diverticulitis with purulent peritonitis in select patients, however, the recurrence rates are minimally worse than a colonic resection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The severity of acute diverticulitis is based on the Hinchey classification system.","Hinchey 0 and 1a acute diverticulitis can be managed as outpatient, without the need for antibiotics in immunocompetent patients.","Hinchey 1b-4 classification of acute diverticulitis should be managed as inpatients and typically require urgent or emergency surgery."],"references":["You H, Cooper M, Von Papern M, Innes J. The management of diverticulitis: a review of the guidelines. Medical Journal of Australia. 2019;211(9). Available at: www.mja.com.au/system/files/issues/211_09/mja250276.pdf","Sartelli M, Weber DG, Kluger Y et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 2020. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4","Gaillard F, Bell D. Hinchey classification of acute diverticulitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. 2008; accessed 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/hinchey-classification-of-acute-diverticulitis","Sijberden J, Snijders H, van Aalten S. Laparoscopic Lavage in Complicated Diverticulitis with Colonic Perforation, Always Be Closing? Case Rep Gastroenterol. 2021;15(2):765-771. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8436632/","Sacks OA, Hall J. Management of Diverticulitis A Review. JAMA Surgery. 2024. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamasurgery/article-abstract/2817649"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-03T08:41:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-03T08:41:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1191"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","